If you are a well known player (not casual !) no problems. Lots of people will invite you, because mages are great DPS, and they know they can trust you.<br>
<br>
If you are a casual player, raiding with your guild and having - from time to time - 2 or 3 hours only for XP, then with POP you are in trouble. There are not much places where you can really solo, and yes solo is much more difficult than when you were 59/60 in the grey or in ME. If you don't have the 61 pet it is even more difficult. <br>
<br>
May be you should try and learn the 'root tecnic' to solo...<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm47.showMessage?topicID=13.topic">pub102.ezboard.com/fthema...D=13.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
another thing : getting a group in POV or POS is rather long if your friends are not up. YES, BUT : when you've got a group, XP is really big big. <br>
I tried my own test :<br>
you've got only 2 hours.<br>
1/ LFG ON, go to POD and solo rats (better have Epic or 61 pet). If 2 come, I prefer to zone out...<br>
2/ LFG ON, go to POV and shout. Wait one hour more or less and get a group for one hour.<br>
<br>
XP is same more or less (well, I must admit I am not a good soloer, it is too boring for me, then I am not well trained)<br>
<br>
if you've got more than 2 hours, then grouping is, of course, much much better, even with loosing one hour LFG.<br>
<br>
Now, i met mages who enjoy solo, who are good at it and can solo 5 hours in a row without falling asleep, and they say XP is same than group, and parchment drop better (.. you are  sure to win roll)<br>
